### Leading a Cross-Functional Product Launch Under a Tight Deadline

**Competencies:** [execution] [leadership] [cross-functional] [communication]
**Role types:** [product] [ops] [chief-of-staff] [general-management]

**Situation:** At Acme Corp, our flagship product was scheduled for a major release in Q4. Six weeks before launch, the engineering lead flagged a critical dependency on a third-party API that had not been scoped into the timeline. The sales team had already begun demoing the feature to enterprise prospects.

**Action:** I called an immediate cross-functional sync with engineering, sales, and legal to understand the full blast radius. I negotiated a 72-hour extension with our top two enterprise prospects by reframing the delay as a stability investment. In parallel, I worked with the engineering lead to identify a simplified fallback that could ship on time, and I personally rewrote the external-facing release notes to accurately reflect the scope change without alarming customers.

**Result:** We shipped on the original date with the fallback implementation. Neither enterprise prospect churned. Three months later, the full feature shipped and both converted to paid contracts worth $420k combined ARR. The cross-functional sync format became a standing weekly ritual adopted by the whole product org.

**30-second version:** At Acme, an undiscoped API dependency threatened to blow a critical product launch six weeks out. I ran a rapid cross-functional sync, bought time with key prospects by repositioning the delay, and found a fallback path that let us ship on time. Both enterprise accounts converted, and the incident became the foundation for a standing cross-functional ritual that improved coordination across the org.

