### Rebuilding Trust After a Team Communication Breakdown

**Competencies:** [leadership] [conflict] [culture] [management]
**Role types:** [ops] [chief-of-staff] [general-management] [people-management]

**Situation:** I inherited a team of four at Globex Inc where two senior members had developed a pattern of going directly to the VP to escalate issues, bypassing the team's agreed process. This was creating confusion and eroding trust across the group.

**Action:** I had direct one-on-ones with both individuals first — not to reprimand, but to understand their reasoning. One had lost confidence that team-level decisions would be acted on quickly. The other had a longstanding relationship with the VP that predated my tenure. I addressed the first by introducing a lightweight weekly decision log that was shared with the VP, making team-level decisions visible without creating bureaucracy. For the second, I invited the VP to briefly join a monthly team retrospective so the relationship channel became part of the official structure rather than a workaround.

**Result:** Direct escalations dropped to near zero within two months. The decision log became a tool the whole team valued for context-setting in cross-team meetings. Both individuals remained strong contributors and one was later promoted.

**30-second version:** At Globex, two senior team members were consistently bypassing team process to escalate directly to the VP. Rather than treating it as a policy violation, I diagnosed the underlying cause for each person and addressed it structurally — a decision log for one, a formalized VP touchpoint for the other. Escalations dropped off, both people stayed engaged, and one was promoted.

